description: Fragment of a clay tablet, 8 lines of inscription, Neo-Assyrian. Fragment out of the middle, part of a text containing incantations and directions for ceremonies.

content.value: Incantation: “[May the temple bring] his temple [back (to health), may the eye bring his eye back (to health), may] the middle (of the head) [bring] his middle (of the head) [back (to health). May he be able to shine, may he be able to shine.” Incantation formula].

parts.text: Incantation: “[May the temple bring] his temple [back (to health), may the eye bring his eye back (to health), may] the middle (of the head) [bring] his middle (of the head) [back (to health). May he be able to shine, may he be able to shine.” Incantation formula].

content.value: Its ritual: [you twist together] male @i{ašlu}-rush [(and) gazelle sinew, you tie on seven and seven knots] (and) with each of (these) knots you recite the incantation. You wrap [male and female @i{ḫallulāyu}-insect (and) ..., which flies over the field], around the knots in red wool [(and) you tie (the string) to his temple].

content.value: [If a man’s left ear is affected, it is full of wind (and) inflamed: on the fifteenth day] of the sixth month, you heat up goose fat (and) while it is still hot, you pour it into his ears]. (Then) you heat up [goose meat], (and) he should eat it. [You pour cedar oil on his head], (and then) he should eat [@i{ḫibṣu}-preparation in @i{saḫlû}-cress].
